# /gybis-memory-synthesize [topic] — Synthesize Knowledge Page

Consolidate memories about `[topic]` into a durable knowledge page.

## Objective

Produce `<root>/mementum/knowledge/[topic].md` — a synthesized document that future AI sessions
can read to understand this topic without replaying all individual memories.

## Step 1: Gather Memories

```bash
git grep -i "[topic]" -- mementum/memories/
git log -n 13 --oneline -- mementum/memories/
```

Read all matching memory files.

## Step 2: Check for Existing Knowledge Page

If `<root>/mementum/knowledge/[topic].md` exists, read it. The synthesis updates rather than
replaces — stale content is the primary signal that an update is needed.

## Step 3: Draft Knowledge Page

Write with frontmatter:

```markdown
---
title: [Topic Title]
status: open
category: [arch | spec | memory | dev]
tags: [relevant-tags]
related: []
depends-on: []
---

[Synthesized content — written for a future AI session, not for humans to approve]
```

Status values: `open → designing → active → done`

## Step 4: Human Approval and Commit

Present the draft to the human. Human approves. AI commits:

```bash
git add mementum/knowledge/[topic].md
git commit -m "💡 synthesize: [topic]"
```

## Key Rules

- Write for a future AI session, not for human review (though humans review before commit)
- Completeness is not required at creation — `open` status is fine
- Knowledge pages are updated in place; memories accumulate as breadcrumbs
- Human approves before any commit
